WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:18.040
We've just gone through how we protect specific vulnerabilities in systems and so forth,

00:18.040 --> 00:34.040
where you know, how do you protect against emanation?

00:34.040 --> 00:38.040
We've just gone through how we protect specific vulnerabilities in systems and so forth,

00:38.040 --> 00:41.600
where you know, how do you protect against emanations and how do you protect against

00:41.600 --> 00:43.640
single points of failure and so forth.

00:43.640 --> 00:47.040
Now let's talk more overall, how do you protect systems?

00:47.040 --> 00:51.040
How do you protect overall systems like an entire mobile device, an entire desktop,

00:51.040 --> 00:54.040
a laptop, or even an entire server?

00:54.040 --> 00:58.040
And the simple way to think about this is that these are wildly complex systems.

00:58.040 --> 01:01.040
Like, even take an example, like my phone.

01:01.040 --> 01:04.040
What hardware and software is in a device like this?

01:04.040 --> 01:07.040
They are remarkably complex devices.

01:07.040 --> 01:12.040
From a hardware perspective, we've got a CPU, we've got RAM, we've got tons of storage.

01:12.040 --> 01:15.040
How about even just from a radio as perspective, how many radios are in this?

01:15.040 --> 01:17.040
Well, is your Wi-Fi?

01:17.040 --> 01:18.040
There's your cellular?

01:18.040 --> 01:19.040
There's your Bluetooth?

01:19.040 --> 01:20.040
There's your RFID?

01:20.040 --> 01:22.040
I mean, that's just four radios right there.

01:22.040 --> 01:23.040
There could be more.

01:23.040 --> 01:27.040
And then from a software perspective, we have a very complicated operating system.

01:27.040 --> 01:29.040
We have multiple apps running on top of that.

01:29.040 --> 01:33.040
What I'm trying to get at is that any of these types of devices, even mobile devices,

01:33.040 --> 01:38.040
and especially after something like a server, they are extremely complex devices.

01:38.040 --> 01:42.040
So how do we go about securing such a complex device?

01:42.040 --> 01:44.040
Well, it's a concept John has already talked about.

01:44.040 --> 01:48.040
To protect anything, you break it down into its components.

01:48.040 --> 01:50.040
And then you protect each of those components.

01:50.040 --> 01:54.040
The more valuable the system, the more time you're going to spend subdividing it

01:54.040 --> 01:56.040
into more and more smaller components.

01:56.040 --> 01:59.040
Rather than just looking at the CPU, you could look at parts of the CPU.

01:59.040 --> 02:03.040
Rather than just looking at the operating system as a whole, you could look at the libraries,

02:03.040 --> 02:05.040
the kernel, the drivers.

02:05.040 --> 02:10.040
You break it down into its components and you secure each of those components.

02:10.040 --> 02:11.040
Here's a good question for you.

02:11.040 --> 02:14.040
You know any devices made up of hardware, software, and so forth?

02:14.040 --> 02:17.040
Where is it hardest to detect vulnerabilities?

02:17.040 --> 02:20.040
This is an exam question that's come up recently.

02:20.040 --> 02:22.040
Where is it hardest?

02:22.040 --> 02:23.040
Hardware.

02:23.040 --> 02:27.040
And the reason being is that we have very well established practices and expertise

02:27.040 --> 02:30.040
in how to detect software malware on our systems as an example.

02:30.040 --> 02:34.040
But there's very few organizations that I've ever come across that will, for instance,

02:34.040 --> 02:38.040
look at a new server that's arrived, just look at every chip on that motherboard

02:38.040 --> 02:44.040
to make sure that someone hasn't installed something in the hardware or some routines in the firmware.

02:44.040 --> 02:50.040
So hardware is, if you've got a question on that, hardware is where it's most difficult to detect vulnerabilities.

02:50.040 --> 02:55.040
Now when we think about when I say to you, you know, you should secure components,

02:55.040 --> 02:57.040
what do I actually mean by that?

02:57.040 --> 03:01.040
And how do you decide what controls to put in place and to what, you know, to what,

03:01.040 --> 03:04.040
how much effort to put into place for controls?

03:04.040 --> 03:07.040
Ultimately what it comes down to is based on organizational relevance.

03:07.040 --> 03:10.040
So security controls need to be based on how valuable.

03:10.040 --> 03:14.040
By the way, that term organizational relevance, what does that really mean?

03:14.040 --> 03:19.040
Well, it means what does this system, this process do with an organization?

03:19.040 --> 03:23.040
What's its organizational relevance, which implies value?

03:23.040 --> 03:24.040
Watch out for that in the exam.

03:24.040 --> 03:29.040
If you see something that says like organizational relevance, it's implying how valuable the system is.

03:29.040 --> 03:33.040
And so we implement controls based on the value of the system, the process.

03:34.040 --> 03:40.040
Specific to mobile systems, things like cell phones, there's one particular technology that I want to talk about.

03:40.040 --> 03:44.040
And that is MDM mobile device management software.

03:44.040 --> 03:46.040
It's essentially like installing big brother on your phone.

03:46.040 --> 03:50.040
It allows a corporation to install a little agent on a device.

03:50.040 --> 03:54.040
The MDM software is an agent that gets installed on an endpoint, like a phone.

03:54.040 --> 03:59.040
And then that software agent allows the corporation to monitor the device,

03:59.040 --> 04:02.040
to implement, to require certain controls.

04:02.040 --> 04:05.040
The MDM software, for instance, will enforce whole drive encryption,

04:05.040 --> 04:08.040
will enforce strong passwords, things like that.

04:08.040 --> 04:10.040
And even things like remote white.

04:10.040 --> 04:12.040
So that's MDM software.

04:12.040 --> 04:17.040
And it can even go to the point of if a device isn't in compliance.

04:17.040 --> 04:20.040
And this is used a lot where organizations allow BYOD or CYOD

04:20.040 --> 04:22.040
bring your own device, carry your own device.

04:22.040 --> 04:26.040
If an organization is allowing people to bring in their personal phones,

04:26.040 --> 04:29.040
it's a very good idea to install this MDM software on those devices,

04:29.040 --> 04:33.040
to make sure that those devices are secure before they're allowed to connect to

04:33.040 --> 04:37.040
and obtain information from the corporate network.

04:37.040 --> 04:39.040
Now, a final piece I want to talk about here.

04:39.040 --> 04:43.040
And this is applied to whenever you want to protect any sort of system.

04:43.040 --> 04:45.040
You go through this process of hardening.

04:45.040 --> 04:47.040
And we've talked about this a couple times now, right?

04:47.040 --> 04:51.040
It's this concept of going through a device, looking very carefully at the configuration,

04:51.040 --> 04:53.040
making sure all the patches are in place,

04:53.040 --> 04:58.040
disabling unnecessary services, installing the appropriate security controls

04:58.040 --> 05:01.040
like anti-mower, host-based firewall, host-based IDS IPS.

05:01.040 --> 05:07.040
It's going through a checklist and locking down any type of device.

05:07.040 --> 05:11.040
And this concept of hardening absolutely applies to how you secure a mobile device,

05:11.040 --> 05:14.040
a laptop, a server.

05:14.040 --> 05:19.040
So there you go. That's how you do a better job of addressing vulnerabilities and systems.

